The third emotionally-evocative event that occurred in The Crypt was one of the last events where you walked through a corridor with cells and things going on inside them. One of the first ones was a man with his head hanging out of a chamber screaming. Another notable one was two mutilated and emaciated beings, one of which was in a dress coat, on the right. They were sitting on the floor. The last cell was a guy in a black cape, a scare actor, who would run around the cell and reach his hands out screaming. He had on black gloves with claws on them. When going around him, he put his hand out right in front of the woman that was in front of our group and he squealed.

RegDesc: I tried to remind myself that it was all fake and that no danger could come to me. It also helped to remind myself that no one could touch me.
EventDesc: The second emotionally evocative event is when we had to walk through the hallway of cells. I remember that one of the first cells on the right had a dummy disguised as a prisoner halfway in a chamber. One of the next ones on the right had a dummy on the ground dressed as a man on the suit. It was emaciated like a skeleton and the torso was ripped a part. Toward the end, the last cell had an actual scare actor and he was dressed in black with a purple cape. He had black gloves on with these long nails/claws and he would walk around the cell looking at you as he grabbed the bars and screamed at you. He would also reach out and put his hand in front of you. When we were on the middle part of the cell that was protruding parallel to the wall, the woman in front of us got scared as the man put his gloved hand directly in front of her face.

I remember that during the second section of the tour, I believe it was Trial 3, we walked into a dark bedroom with a woman in a red dress. I remember we had to walk around the bed and on the right side of the bed (if looking at the headboard from the foot of the bed) there was a brunette woman in a red dress with a black boa. She was talking distraughtly and you passed her as you were leaving. I want to say she was either on the verge of singing, or singing at some points.

EventDesc: Walking inside and having it immediately be pitch black. I could tell that there was a man waiting in the dark corner, but I couldn't see well enough to tell when he would come out. I tried to walk to the left, away from him, but was pushed towards him by another actor who was wielding a cinderblock. The actor in the shadows attempted to hit me with a pipe.

When we walked out into the outdoor garden, there was a man with a chainsaw who was near the group ahead of us. I stopped, but there were two people behind me, so I had to keep going. The man walked up towards me, not to fast, but then lunged and turned the chainsaw on at the level of my knees. I screamed and then laughed while I tried to run away.

At the beginning of the crypt, I saw we were entering a bus and was excited but a bit nervous. It was dark inside so I couldn't see anything that offered any hints as to what could be inside. Once we were allowed in, we walked up the steep 2-3 steps into the bus, which was practically pitch black. The lights may have been flashing a bit, though that could have been light seeping in from the windows. The freakiest part was that most of the people sitting on the school bus seats were just dummies, but the space between us and them as we walked down the middle aisle was so small that I was very worried one of them would pop up right in my face. I was glad to be directly behind someone for this part. The only real actor I saw was towards the back left, and they had on one of those dead gray masks. They were already in another person's face ahead of me, though, so I knew their location and wasn't as nervous after that.

The first thing that happened was that we were packed into a room with a bunch of people for an orientation and rules. There was a stage with a man with skeleton face paint and a clear face shield, and the walls had been covered with a gray wallpaper. The lighting was dim and had a slight orange tint to it. The woman making the announcement was wearing a Victorian-era looking dress and top hat and was holding a cane. There were also skulls around the room and torches too I believe. I remember her making comments about "we won't bite" and the safe word to get out being "Be nice, ghoul". They also offered the red glow sticks if we wanted a more intense experience, which I did and wish I had taken! Needless to say I was excited and intrigued about what was to come.

EventDesc: In Delirium, I remember first stepping into the area with my 3D glasses on and thinking how strange and also cool the scenery was. Everything was distorted and coming out towards me. I was putting my hands out trying to feel for where exactly the walls, pipes, and props started. The neon colors only added to the strangeness of it all. It had been years since I had worn 3D glasses and was not used to it.

RegDesc: I walked quickly past the area.
EventDesc: Also in the crypt, in the jail cell maze, there was a point when we passed an actor who was literally hanging from the bars/perched on one of the cells in the air. That was freaky because they were RIGHT up at my face level, on my right side. I was very worried it would touch me. I had to turn my face away and cower into my roommate to the left to avoid making eye contact with it. It didn't try anything luckily, just made a growling noise. Right after that was when we ran into the crazy lady and the hanging flashing box.

RegDesc: I quickly got out of that room! And looked away and never looked back at the man
EventDesc: The scariest thing that happened for me was in the meat locker in the Crypt. We walked into this big room where strobe lights were flashing and I could barely see. There was a wall to our left and bodies hanging in bags from meat hooks to our right. I can only remember seeing one actor in that room, but he was in the far right corner when we walked in and suddenly was right up in my face when we stepped into the middle of the room. It actually caused me to make a noise (I don't really scream when scared) and hide my face while holding my roommate's hand and walking quickly to get out of there.

RegDesc: I tried to calm myself down by reminding myself that them being in my face was not a big deal. They were actors trying to make the experience fun for me (which they did).
EventDesc: I was at the back of the group and the actor scared the person in front of me but failed to make me jump. The actor went up to me and said "you're not scared are you." He then followed me for a little bit and snarled in my face. The snarling in the face caused me to laugh. I'm not sure why I laughed but I laughed every time the actors got in my face. I think it was because I was a bit uncomfortable with having the actor so close to my face.
Emotion: uncomfortable when they were in my face

RegDesc: I tried to really immerse myself in the haunted house. This was the most fun haunted house because it felt more interactive and actually succeeded in evoking some sort of emotional response. The first couple of haunted houses were a little boring/unscary so I was excited to have something that actually got me excited.

EventDesc: The school bus was creepy because it had many dead bodies sitting in the seats. The dead bodies were pretty evenly spaced and were one to each seat. The live actor was standing on the seat and seemed to be wearing a gown.

RegDesc: I attempted to intensify my feeling of amusement by making a comment about it to Steven
EventDesc: When we were walking into Delirium, there were two women dancing on the table right at the entrance of the haunted house. They were dressed in dresses and moving very slowly. I remember thinking this was funny because what is scary about dancers? I remember making a comment to Steven about the dancers.

In one of the sections, there was a dentist working on someone in their chair. I remember seeing something (a head?) with teeth all over it and being kind of disturbed by that site. Teeth being all over something isn't necessarily scary but it's pretty gross.

There was a point at the beginning of a section (or maybe in between, I'm not sure) when Steven had his computer out. One of the actors saw this and came up to us. The actor would not say verbally what he came over to us for, but he kept looking at the computer and pointing and grunting. He stayed in character while trying to enforce the rules. I was confused at first on what he wanted since he wouldn't say anything in words, but then I thought it was funny that he came over and insisted on staying in character.

EventDesc: The emotionally-evocative event that occurred was how claustrophobic the bus was, it was super narrow and dark and I do not have a fear of narrow spaces, but knowing there were possible actors in the dark to scare us and there was nowhere to go was slightly scary.

EventDesc: When we walked outside after the last exhibit, Crypt, I saw that there was an Al Capone exhibit. I was curious to look inside, but I had to stay with the group.

When we entered the crypt exhibit, we were on a schoolbus. There were an array of dummies and live actors sitting in the seats. It was dimly lit. There was a ratty looking dummy woman who was facing downwards sitting in the first left-hand seat. I thought she kind of looked like a prostitute.

Towards the end of crypt, there was a walkway with many cages, nets, and foliage. We went up steps and we were eventually above the caged area. There were two large hanging demons that loomed above the area. They looked very eerie, silhouetted against the dim lighting of the hallway.

the pretty lights on the ceiling right at the end. They were very pretty just to stare up at. The relatively big space made me feel suddenly alone, but in a wholesome way. In the way that you feel tiny when looking at the stars at night, or in the way that life sometimes just takes you for a new ride that you have little control over. In the moment it is nerve wracking, but if you're able to make it out unscathed, you can look at the bigger picture and appreciate the intricacies of life a little bit more than before. It reminded me of how small everyone is in a very humbling way.

In the Crypt when we got to the cell block that hanging box with the flashing bright blue/green/white light caught my attention.  I felt I could stare at this a bit longer because I was not fearful anything was going to come out because of how bulky, heavy looking and buttoned up (in terms of appearing secured) it was.  I also remember it being very loud banging/clanging and I feel I could not hear anything else going on besides what was in there.

RegDesc: I could not take any action to limit this feeling of unbalance.  Any action whether it was closing my eyes or focusing on one object straight ahead neglected focusing on small steps or seeing my feet so I went through feeling dizzy/unbalanced and unable to reduce the emotion (feeling).
EventDesc: The second emotionally-evocative was the spinning tunnel and moving footbridge.  I This was so because I remember exclaiming how "trippy" I thought this was due to the 3-D glasses and lights that were on the spinning tunnel, and the off-kilter and moving footbridge really making me dizzy and feeling like I was going to fall.

RegDesc: I wrote this in because I'm confused and don't recall which one I marked as "falling".  I thought it was in relation to the platform in Crypt that moved back and forth but I had documented that in the previous one that I called Bridge.  The only other platform that moved I could think of was in Delirium with the footbridge in the tunnel but I had previously documented that and called that one Tunnel.
EventDesc: In the Crypt after we had walked upstairs there was a section that had a bridge/platform that reminded me of one of those speed-walker flat escalators you see at the airport that help you go from one section to another faster.  This stood out because I remember being on it and thinking of the scene Elf where Will Ferrell does his split on the escalator which made me laugh.  But at the same time I thought I was going to fall over on this thing and been embarrassed because my girlfriend would have thought it to be the funniest thing in the world.  Plus there was a group of random people behind me (I was the last in our study group line) so I was concerned they would laugh and/or fall  on top of me.

RegDesc: As I mentioned in the immediate debrief, I am a firefighter so when we were walking through this section and were greeted by the odor of gas and exhaust fumes, even before the saw sound was heard it reminded me of shift change at the firehouse as part of this shift change is fueling and starting the saws to make sure they are in order.  As such, the smell of gasoline and exhaust fumes are what I equate to morning shift change so by thinking of this it make me feel more comfortable of my surrounding, and also expect the actual chainsaw to follow.
EventDesc: The second was the smell of the gasoline just before walking outside of the building to the woman running with the chainsaw.  I think I remembered this the most cause it reminded me of shift change at the firehouse when the crew starts up the saws.

RegDesc: I was concerned about falling over so I tried to reduce it by taking slow and small steps but my impaired senses were throwing me off so it was not very successful.

This was emotionally evocative because the strobe light and decreased visibility due to smoke really made me feel as if I was "skipping frames" in real life, and everyone time I saw a flash the person in front of me was in a different spot and the actors walking about appeared or vanished like that.  Also, there was one point where the line stopped for some reason and an actor bumped into me and apologized                          because he knew they were not allowed to touch us and kept saying he did not anticipate the line stopping like that.

The third most evocative event was the hand in the table saw.  I think it was because most of the tour it was eyes front staying in line trying not to really react or be susceptible to the actors, so when I saw something I felt comfortable with looking at/investigating a little more I took the time to remember it.

RegDesc: I tried to take my time on this thing but quickly realized the faster I got off the faster I was back on stable ground.
EventDesc: I did not know if this was part of one of the sets but I would be remiss if I did not mention it.  This is the long tunnel that we entered before the Shop set.  This was emotionally evocative because the strobe light and decreased visibility due to smoke really made me feel as if I was "skipping frames" in real life, and everyone time I saw a flash the person in front of me was in a different spot and the actors walking about appeared or vanished like that.  Also, there was one point where the line stopped for some reason and an actor bumped into me and apologized                          because he knew they were not allowed to touch us and kept saying he did not anticipate the line stopping like that.

In Take 13, the bright red dress woman singing opera was very emotionally-evocative.  It was a bit unexpected and probably stood out because we had just entered from the monochromatic newsroom with an announcement from a man with a relatively deep voice into this room that was dark but still had a gold light and woman in a red flowing dress singing opera.

RegDesc: I tried to inspect around a little more to intensify the interested emotion because I was genuinely surprised how they were able to create such a defined smoke level line with maintaining a level of visibility above it.  Usually the dynamics of smoke are such that visibility is greater in the lower compartment of a room rather than the higher end.  Seeing this reversed piqued my interest.
EventDesc: The first event was the scene in Delirium that had the smoke filled room and neon lasers about, with the smoke really settling on a fine and identifiable level/layer within the height of the room.  I was surprised with how much I could see considering how dark the room was and how much smoke there was.

RegDesc: I was fearful that this was a distraction from a set-up, so I tried to look away and keep my general awareness of what was going on visually, but the sound was too loud for me to fully focus.
EventDesc: In the Crypt when we got to the cell block that hanging box with the flashing bright blue/green/white light caught my attention.  I felt I could stare at this a bit longer because I was not fearful anything was going to come out because of how bulky, heavy looking and buttoned up (in terms of appearing secured) it was.  I also remember it being very loud banging/clanging and I feel I could not hear anything else going on besides what was in there.

EventDesc: Wandering through the bus: we stepped aboard a silver, metallic bus that had metallic stairs. There was no driver, or at least a plexiglass was shielding him. The bus was dark, and there was flashing white light at a rapid interval. Figures were bent, heads down, one on every over row/seat or so. None of them lunged, thankfully, but I made my way through the aisle as quickly as possible. We descended the ramp and left the bus.
Education.Cat: Graduate school degree (MA, MS, PhD, etc.)

RegDesc: I laughed, and tried to enjoy the moment
EventDesc: The hallway of cages: we wandered through a dark, foggy room/hallway populated with small cages. Inside were zombie looking patients, someone wrapped in white cloth and sitting up, and a figure with an arm poking out of its chest. There were things hanging from the ceiling, and people who'd occasionally chase me or try and scare me. There was also a box that would rattle. We finally left that room.
Education.Cat: Graduate school degree (MA, MS, PhD, etc.)

RegDesc: I tried to breathe through being scared and remind myself they were actors or props and couldn't touch me
EventDesc: Walking through the bus- I remember flashing lights and having a hard time seeing, I was afraid of the people sitting in the seats and spend time trying to figure out whether or not they were real but it was really hard to tell because of the flashing lights. I remember at the end there was one real actor that jumped at the person in front of me and I was thankful that it wasn't me so I wouldn't scream.

RegDesc: I tried to get used to the noise and figure out the pattern of the box noise as well as figure out how the prop was making the noise
EventDesc: I remember being next to the cell with a box that was banging. I remember figuring out that there was nobody real inside so nobody will jump out at me but it was really loud and I was standing next to it for a long time. The sound was scarier to me than the actual concept of a crazy person in a box in a cell.

RegDesc: I tried to get through the room as fast as possible and keep moving forward focusing on where I was walking
EventDesc: The freezer with the hanging bodies  was the most scared I was in any section. I remember again being uneasy that I couldn't see and the bodies were swinging so I felt like I was gonna knock into them. And while I was focused on how to avoid the bodies I was aware that there was a live actor near me. I think they could tell I was uneasy and he got in my ear and started growling.I laughed/screamed and I remember regretting it because I knew he would follow me and he did. I was too scared to look at his face and also wanted to keep facing forward so I wouldn't knock into anything so even though I knew he was near me it was hard to tell how close. Right before I exited the room her growled again and I screamed again.
